\details{
\subsection{Understanding the Results}{

The frequency table shows:
\itemize{
\item \strong{Freq}: Number of responses in each category
\item \strong{\%}: Percentage including missing values (use for "response rate")
\item \strong{Valid \%}: Percentage excluding missing values (use for "among those who answered")
\item \strong{Cum \%}: Running total percentage (helps identify cutoff points)
}
}

\subsection{When to Use This}{

Use \code{frequency()} when you have:
\itemize{
\item Categorical variables (gender, region, education level)
\item Yes/No questions
\item Rating scales (satisfied/neutral/dissatisfied)
\item Any question with a fixed set of options
}
}

\subsection{Weights Make a Difference}{

Without weights, you're describing your sample. With weights, you're estimating
population values. Always use weights for population inference.
}

\subsection{Tagged Missing Values}{

When data is imported with tagged NAs (e.g., via \code{\link[=read_spss]{read_spss()}} with
\code{tag_na = TRUE}, or \code{\link[=read_stata]{read_stata()}}, \code{\link[=read_sas]{read_sas()}}, \code{\link[=read_xpt]{read_xpt()}} with the
\code{tag_na} parameter), \code{frequency()} automatically expands the missing value
section to show each missing type individually (with its original missing
value code and label), plus summary rows for \strong{Total Valid} and \strong{Total
Missing}.
}
}
